    <!-- SCIENCE SECTION -->
    <h2 id="science">The Science Behind Fiber and Probiotics for Constipation</h2>

    <p>The clinical evidence supporting fiber and probiotic supplementation for constipation relief is among the strongest in the dietary supplement space. Major systematic reviews and meta-analyses published in high-impact journals consistently demonstrate that increasing fiber intake and introducing beneficial probiotic bacteria improve bowel frequency, stool consistency, and overall digestive comfort in both healthy adults and those with functional constipation.</p>

    <div class="info-cards">
      <div class="info-card">
        <strong>Fiber intake: strong evidence (Lancet 2019)</strong>
        <p>A meta-analysis of 185 studies and 58 trials confirmed that 25-29g daily fiber significantly improves stool frequency, reduces straining, and lowers colorectal cancer risk by 15-30%. Psyllium and wheat dextrin show the most consistent results.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <strong>Probiotics for transit time: strong evidence</strong>
        <p>A 2014 AJCN meta-analysis of 14 RCTs found probiotics reduced gut transit time by 12.4 hours and increased weekly stool frequency by 1.3 bowel movements. Bifidobacterium and Lactobacillus strains were most effective.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <strong>Psyllium for constipation: strong evidence</strong>
        <p>A 2020 systematic review in the British Journal of General Practice confirmed psyllium is the only fiber with consistent evidence for improving stool frequency, consistency, and straining across multiple constipation populations.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <strong>PHGG for gentle relief: moderate evidence</strong>
        <p>Partially hydrolyzed guar gum (PHGG) has been shown to normalize bowel function in both constipation and diarrhea with the least gas production of any studied fiber — making it uniquely suited for IBS patients.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

