    <!-- FAQ SECTION -->
    <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions About Gummies for Constipation</h2>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Do fiber gummies actually help with constipation?</summary>
      <p>Yes. Fiber gummies containing soluble fiber like inulin, psyllium, or wheat dextrin absorb water in the colon, soften stool, and stimulate peristalsis. A 2019 Lancet meta-analysis confirmed that increasing fiber intake to 25-29g daily significantly improves stool frequency and consistency. While gummies provide 3-6g per serving — not the full daily need — they meaningfully supplement dietary fiber, especially for individuals with consistently low fiber intake.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>How much fiber per day do I need for regular bowel movements?</summary>
      <p>The American Dietetic Association recommends 25g daily for women and 38g for men. Most Americans consume only 15g. Increasing fiber by 10-15g per day shows significant constipation improvement in clinical trials. Fiber gummies providing 3-6g per serving are a supplement to dietary fiber from fruits, vegetables, whole grains, and legumes — not a replacement for fiber-rich foods.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>What is the difference between soluble and insoluble fiber?</summary>
      <p>Soluble fiber dissolves in water to form a gel that softens stool (psyllium, inulin, wheat dextrin). Insoluble fiber adds bulk and speeds transit (wheat bran, cellulose). Most fiber gummies use soluble fiber because it blends into gummy formulations. Both types help constipation: soluble softens stool, insoluble adds bulk. A dietary combination of both produces the best results.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Are probiotic gummies better than fiber gummies for constipation?</summary>
      <p>They address different mechanisms. Fiber adds bulk and softens stool. Probiotics improve gut motility by modifying the microbiome. A 2014 AJCN meta-analysis found probiotics reduce transit time by 12.4 hours and increase stool frequency by 1.3 per week. For chronic constipation, combining both fiber and probiotics often produces superior results to either alone.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>How long does it take for fiber gummies to relieve constipation?</summary>
      <p>Improved regularity typically begins within 2-3 days, with full effects stabilizing at 1-2 weeks. Psyllium (Metamucil) works fastest — 12-72 hours — because it absorbs water rapidly. Prebiotic fibers like inulin take 5-7 days as they work partly through gut bacteria modification. Always drink 8+ ounces of water with fiber gummies for optimal results.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Can fiber gummies cause bloating or gas?</summary>
      <p>Yes, particularly during the first 1-2 weeks. Gut bacteria ferment soluble fiber, producing gas as a byproduct. Inulin and chicory root cause more gas than wheat dextrin or PHGG. Start at half dose for 7-14 days, then increase gradually. Sunfiber (PHGG) is clinically shown to produce the least gas of any fiber type and is FODMAP Friendly Certified for sensitive individuals.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Should I take fiber gummies with or without food?</summary>
      <p>Either works, but taking with meals may reduce gas in sensitive individuals. The most important factor is drinking at least 8 ounces of water — fiber needs water to form the stool-softening gel. Taking fiber 30 minutes before meals can promote satiety. For constipation, consistency matters most: same time daily helps establish a predictable bowel routine.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Are fiber gummies safe for children with constipation?</summary>
      <p>Many fiber gummies are formulated for children aged 4+. The AAP recommends child fiber intake equal to age plus 5g daily (e.g., 11g for a 6-year-old). Children's fiber gummies typically provide 2-4g per serving. Choose age-appropriate products, ensure adequate water intake, and consult a pediatrician before supplementing children under 4 or with chronic constipation.</p>
    </details>

